wever, the Lincoln recruits soon encountered suspicious military leaders who questioned their patriotism and denied them promotions and overseas assignments, foreshadowing the political persecution of the postwar Red Scare. African American veterans who fought in fully integrated units in Spain, faced second-class treatment in America's Jim Crow army. Nevertheless, the Lincolns served with distinction in every theater of the war and won a disproportionate number of medals for courage, dedication, and sacrifice.The 154 letters in this volume, selected from thousands held in the Abraham Lincoln Brigade Archives at NYU’s Tamiment Library, provide a new and unique perspective on aspects of World War II.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAnti-fascist movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSoldierszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, American. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xParticipation, African American. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xPublic opinion. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aAbraham.  aBrigade.  aLincoln.  aWorld.  aWritten.  aanti-fascist.  aboot.  acamps.  acockpits.  aexperienced.  aexpress.  afoxholes.  aglobal.  agreat.  aidealism.  aintelligence.  aissues.  aletters.  alost.  anever.  apassion.  asight.  asoldiers.  astake.  awith.1 aCarroll, Peter N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNash, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmall, Melvin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814772973423Coveruhttps://www.degruy